Joshi et al. [25] reviewed the current national and international test standards for thermosyphon type solar DHW systems. They rated the Taiwan Testing Standard CNS B7277 as the best stationary outdoor test standard, which does not specify any hot water withdrawal pattern. Huang et al. [26, 27] studied the effects of storage mass and asymmetric variation of solar radiation and suggested corrective measures for CNS B7277. So CNS can be used to compare the daily performance of different systems and hence can be used for collector rating purpose. But the CNS standard does not rate the shorter term heat acquisition and night-time storage heat loss. On the other hand, the Chinese National Standard GB/T 12915-91 [28] and GB/T 18708-2002 [29] can be used to test the transient system performance and the night-time storage heat loss respectively. Accordingly, in this study the performance ratings of the WG and HP types were compared in the following aspects:


daily system efficiency, according to the Taiwan Testing Standard CNS B7277: the thermal performance test of thermosyphon solar water heaters [30];

transient system efficiency, according to the Chinese National Standard GB/T 12915-91: the experimental method for the thermal performance of home solar heater;

night-time system coefficient of heat loss, according to the Chinese National Standard GB/T 18708-2002: test methods for thermal performance of domestic solar water heating systems.

According to the GB/T 12915-91, the transient efficiency ηt of the collector is given by (4) where Ti and Ti+1 are the water temperatures at the start and the end of the time interval Δτ respectively; Hi and Hi+1 are the accumulated solar radiation at the start and the end of the same measuring interval, respectively. This measuring interval should be within 15–60 min. In our study, the calculation time interval was 30 min. There are two criteria in the selection of calculation period, that is:
the average water temperature Tw in the tank is higher that the ambient temperature Ta;
Tw should never be descending in the calculation period.
